Citation Metadata
description
The main title of the Physical Sample
A secondary title that amplifies or states certain limitations on the main title
Either 1) a title commonly used to refer to the Physical Sample or 2) an abbreviation of the main title
Another URL where one can view or access the metadata of the Physical Sample, e.g. a project or personal webpage
Another unique identifier for the Physical Sample (e.g. producer's or another repository's identifier or code)
The name of the agency that generated the other identifier or code
Another identifier or code uniquely identifies the Physical Sample
The entity, e.g. a person or organization, that created or collected the Physical Sample
The name of the author, such as the person's name or the name of an organization
column5: 1) Family Name, Given Name or 2) Organization XYZ

column4: The name of the entity affiliated with the author, e.g. an organization's name
The type of identifier that uniquely identifies the author (e.g. ORCID, ISNI)
Uniquely identifies the author when paired with an identifier type
The entity, e.g. a person or organization, that users of the Physical Sample can contact with questions
The name of the point of contact, e.g. the person's name or the name of an organization
The name of the entity affiliated with the point of contact, e.g. an organization's name
The point of contact's email address
A summary describing the purpose, nature, and scope of the Physical Sample
A summary describing the purpose, nature, and scope of the Physical Sample

The date when the description was added to the Physical Sample. If the Physical Sample contains more than one description, e.g. the sample producer supplied one description and the sample repository supplied another, this date is used to distinguish between the descriptions
The area of study relevant to the Physical Sample based on ANZSRC Fields of Research (FoR)
A key term that describes an important aspect of the Physical Sample and information about any controlled vocabulary used
A key term that describes important aspects of the Physical Sample
The controlled vocabulary used for the keyword term (e.g. LCSH, MeSH)
The URL where one can access information about the term's controlled vocabulary
Indicates a broad, important topic or subject that the Physical Sample covers and information about any controlled vocabulary used
A topic or subject term
The controlled vocabulary used for the keyword term (e.g. LCSH, MeSH)
The URL where one can access information about the term's controlled vocabulary
The article or report that uses the data of the Physical Sample. The full list of related publications will be displayed on the metadata tab
The full bibliographic citation for the related publication
The type of identifier that uniquely identifies a related publication
The identifier for a related publication

The URL form of the identifier entered in the Identifier field, e.g. the DOI URL if a DOI was entered in the Identifier field. Used to display what was entered in the ID Type and ID Number fields as a link. If what was entered in the Identifier field has no URL form, the URL of the publication webpage is used, e.g. a journal article webpage
Additional information about the Physical Sample
A language that the Physical Sample's files is written in
The entity, such a person or organization, managing the finances or other administrative processes involved in the creation of the Physical Sample
The name of the entity, e.g. the person's name or the name of an organization
The name of the entity affiliated with the producer, e.g. an organization's name
The producer's abbreviated name (e.g. IQSS, ICPSR)
The URL of the producer's website
The URL of the producer's logo
The date when the data were produced (not distributed, published, or archived)
The location where the data and any related materials were produced or collected
The entity, such as a person or organization, responsible for collecting, managing, or otherwise contributing to the development of the Physical Sample
Indicates the type of contribution made to the dataset
The name of the contributor, e.g. the person's name or the name of an organization
Information about the Physical Sample's financial support
The agency that provided financial support for the Physical Sample
The grant identifier or contract identifier of the agency that provided financial support for the Physical Sample
The entity, such as a person or organization, designated to generate copies of the Physical Sample, including any editions or revisions
The name of the entity, e.g. the person's name or the name of an organization
The name of the entity affiliated with the distributor, e.g. an organization's name
The distributor's abbreviated name (e.g. IQSS, ICPSR)
The URL of the distributor's webpage
The URL of the distributor's logo image, used to show the image on the Physical Sample's page
The date when the Physical Sample was made available for distribution/presentation
The entity, such as a person or organization, that deposited the record of the Physical Sample in the repository
The date when the Physical Sample record was deposited into the repository
The time period that the data refer to. Also known as span. This is the time period covered by the data, not the dates of coding, collecting data, or making documents machine-readable
The start date of the time period that the data refer to
The end date of the time period that the data refer to
The dates when the sample were collected or generated
The date when the sample collection started
The date when the sample collection ended
The method by which the sample was collected/created.
Information about the dataset series to which the Physical Sample belong
The name of the dataset series
Can include 1) a history of the series and 2) a summary of features that apply to the series
Information about the software used to generate the Physical Sample
The name of software used to generate the Physical Sample
The version of the software used to generate the Physical Sample, e.g. 4.11
Information, such as a persistent ID or citation, about the material related to the Physical Sample, such as appendices or sampling information available outside of the Physical Sample
Information, such as a persistent ID or citation, about a related dataset, such as previous research on the Physical Sample
Information, such as a persistent ID or citation, about another type of resource that provides background or supporting material to the Physical Sample
Information, such as a persistent ID or citation, about sources of the Physical Sample (e.g. a book, article, serial, or machine-readable data file)
For historical sources, the origin and any rules followed in establishing them as sources
Characteristics not already noted elsewhere
1) Methods or procedures for accessing samples and 2) any special permissions needed for access
